# Rust Backend Rules

## Tauri Commands

- Every `#[tauri::command]` must return `Result<T, String>` or a custom error type
- Register all commands in `tauri::generate_handler![]` in `lib.rs`
- Validate all arguments — never trust data from the frontend
- Keep commands thin: delegate business logic to service modules

```rust
// Good: thin command, delegates to service
#[tauri::command]
async fn get_balance(chain_id: u64, address: String) -> Result<String, String> {
    let addr = validate_address(&address).map_err(|e| e.to_string())?;
    services::chain::get_balance(chain_id, addr)
        .await
        .map_err(|e| e.to_string())
}
```

## Error Handling

- Use `thiserror` for domain errors
- Never `.unwrap()` — use `.map_err()`, `?` operator, or `.expect("reason")` for provably safe cases
- User-facing error messages must not expose internal paths, stack traces, or system info

## Security

- Key material: use `zeroize` crate, drop keys immediately after signing
- OS keychain only for key storage — no file-based key stores
- All transaction amounts must be validated for overflow before math operations
- Use `ring` or `sodiumoxide` for cryptographic operations — never roll custom crypto

## Async & Background Tasks

- Use Tokio for all async work; never `std::thread::sleep` on the Tokio runtime
- Background strategies must be cancellable via `CancellationToken`
- Send progress/results to frontend via `app_handle.emit("event_name", payload)`
- Respect user-defined guardrails (spending limits, stop conditions) in every execution loop

## Dependencies

- Pin versions (e.g., `serde = "1.0.210"` not `serde = "1"`) for reproducible builds
- Prefer minimal, audited crates
- Run `cargo audit` before adding new dependencies
